Piping, Filtering and Sorting Data

## Lab Overview
This lab will cover the basics of Piping, Filtering and Sorting in Powershell

### Objectives
- Understand the mechanics behind Piping and it's various uses
- Identify fundemental cmdlets and commands that can be used to make searching through data an easier task
- Learn how piping, filtering, sorting is used by IT professoinals for analysis

## Key Concepts

| Piping | use of the pipe operator "|". sends objects produced from onecommand through another command. |
| Objects | Representations of items or 'states' in Powershell |
| Sort-Object | sorts objecs in ascending or descending order. Based on object 'property values'(name, length, status) |
| Length | Object property, commonly meaning 'size of a file in bytes'.
| Where-Object | Filters objects in Powershell. Selects 'objects that have particular property values'(from a collection of objects passed to it) |
| Extension | file property sucha as .txt, .log, .ps1. Can be used as a way to filter data |
| -eq | Comparison operator. Can test whether (2) values are equal. Can be used in conjunction with where-object as a form of filter |
| -ne | Comaprison operator. Tests whether (2) values are not-equal. Helpful for status filtering |
| -gt | Comparison operator. Tests whether (1) object is greater than another object. Helpful for size filtering |
| -lt | Comaprison operator. Tests whether the left-hand object is less than another object. Helpful for sorting data by date |
| -le | Comparison operator. tests whether the left-hand object is less than or equal to antoher object. Can be used for data sorting or size filtering. |
| -like | Checks whether 'something' matches a pattern. usually with * as a wildcard |
| Select-String | search command(for text). Similar to 'grep' in Linux. Useful for searching logs, configs, scripts and output of other commands |
| Select-Object | the objects returned will only show the specific properties designated after the command |

