## Lab Walkthrough

### Syntax: Get-ChildItem | Sort-Object Length

PS C:\Users\captain\Documents\captain-cabin> Get-ChildItem | Sort-Object Length

    Directory: C:\Users\captain\Documents\captain-cabin

Mode                 LastWriteTime         Length Name
----                 -------------         ------ ----
-a----          9/4/2024  12:50 PM              0 captain-boots.txt
-a----          9/4/2024  12:14 PM            264 captain-hat2.txt
-a----          9/4/2024  12:14 PM            264 captain-hat.txt
-a----          9/4/2024  12:37 PM           2116 ship-flag.txt
d-----          9/4/2024  12:50 PM                captain-wardrobe

- presented all items inside the captain-cabin folder
- sorted the contents of this folder based on the length(in bytes) of each .txt file
- sorted smallest to largest
- "-a----" means file
- "d-----" means directory
- typing -descending at the end of the command line would sort the files starting with the largest

### Syntax: Get-ChildItem | Where-Object -Property "Extension" -eq ".txt" 

PS C:\Users\captain\Documents\captain-cabin> Get-ChildItem | Where-Object -Property "Extension" -eq ".txt" 

    Directory: C:\Users\captain\Documents\captain-cabin

Mode                 LastWriteTime         Length Name
----                 -------------         ------ ----
-a----          9/4/2024  12:50 PM              0 captain-boots.txt
-a----          9/4/2024  12:14 PM            264 captain-hat.txt
-a----          9/4/2024  12:14 PM            264 captain-hat2.txt
-a----          9/4/2024  12:37 PM           2116 ship-flag.txt

- retrieved the items in the captain-cabin folder
- kept only the items that had the file extension ".txt"

### Syntax: Get-ChildItem | Where-Object -Property "Name" -like "ship*"  

PS C:\Users\captain\Documents\captain-cabin> Get-ChildItem | Where-Object -Property "Name" -like "ship*"  

    Directory: C:\Users\captain\Documents\captain-cabin

Mode                 LastWriteTime         Length Name
----                 -------------         ------ ----
-a----          9/4/2024  12:37 PM           2116 ship-flag.txt

- retrieved the contents of the folder
- kept only the items whose 'Name' property matched the pattern "ship*"
- the wildcard "*" meant that as long as the first part of the Name was "ship" any item woul be part of the collection

### Syntax: Get-ChildItem | Select-Object Name,Length 

PS C:\Users\captain\Documents\captain-cabin> Get-ChildItem | Select-Object Name,Length 

Name              Length
----              ------
captain-wardrobe
captain-boots.txt 0
captain-hat.txt   264
captain-hat2.txt  264
ship-flag.txt     2116

- retrieved items from the folder
- only showed the Name and Length properties as part of the data set

### Syntax: Select-String -Path ".\captain-hat.txt" -Pattern "hat" 

PS C:\Users\captain\Documents\captain-cabin> Select-String -Path ".\captain-hat.txt" -Pattern "hat" 

captain-hat.txt:8:Don't touch my hat!

- searched the file captain-hat.txt for the text pattern "hat"(within the .txt. file)
- returned the line number the match was found
- returned the contents of the line that contained the match

## Security Relevance
- Security work requires searching through a LOT of system, network, user, process and log data
- Being able to isolate important data and read it quickly is critical to good defense work
  - failed logins
  - .ps1 scripts
  - files larger than an expected size
  - files with a known malicious name
  - connections in certain state
    - may be hard to find if data is not organized/isolated, due to volume of data logs
- valuable for threat hunting/malware investigation

